TI  - Conditions Attributable to Obesity in Older Adults in the U.S.: A Cross-Sectional 
      Study.
PG  - 108419
LID - S0749-3797(26)00162-5 [pii]
LID - 10.1016/j.amepre.2026.108419 [doi]
AB  - INTRODUCTION: Obesity is prevalent among older adults and can lead to 
      obesity-related conditions (ORC), but aging can also drive the development of 
      these same conditions. Estimating the population attributable fraction (PAF) for 
      ORCs due to obesity may clarify the potential benefit of obesity prevention and 
      treatment in this population. METHODS: This was a cross-sectional study of 
      National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (years 2017-2023), analyzed in 
      2025. Adults aged ≥65 years with body mass index (BMI) ≥18.5 kg/m² were included. 
      Using complex survey methods, prevalences and adjusted relative risks of ORCs 
      among individuals with and without obesity (BMI ≥30 kg/m²) were estimated. These 
      estimates were used to calculate PAFs, representing the proportion of each ORC 
      attributable to obesity. RESULTS: The cohort included 4,029 individuals 
      representing 50,755,846 older adults (mean age 73 (SE 0.2) years, 55.3% female, 
      40.2% with obesity). Population attributable fractions due to obesity were 
      statistically significant for congestive heart failure (33.3% [24.7-39.7]), 
      diabetes (25.3% [20.4-29.5]), asthma (19.4% [6.0-29.0]), metabolic 
      dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease (17.9% [14.3-21.2]), 
      obesity-associated cancer (12.3% [1.9-20.3]), urinary incontinence (10.6% 
      [7.6-13.3]), arthritis (10.9% [7.5-14.0]), coronary artery disease (10.3% 
      [3.3-16.0]), chronic kidney disease (9.2% [2.2-15.1]), hypertension (9.3% 
      [7.3-11.1]), probable obstructive sleep apnea (8.7% [5.2-11.9]), and dyslipidemia 
      (5.8% [3.2-8.2]) but not stroke. CONCLUSIONS: In older adults, multiple ORCs were 
      substantially attributable to obesity, although development of ORCs was still 
      possible outside of obesity. Future work is needed to determine the extent to 
      which modern obesity treatments can reduce the burden of these ORCs in older 
      adults.
